  <div class="container">
    <h1>Best Monthly Dividend Stocks for 2026</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A curated list of the best monthly dividend-paying stocks, including REITs, BDCs, and more, for reliable income every single month.</p>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2>What Are Monthly Dividend Stocks?</h2>
      <div class="guide-content">
        <p>While the vast majority of publicly traded companies pay dividends quarterly, a select group of companies choose to distribute their profits to shareholders on a <strong>monthly</strong> basis. For income investors, retirees, or anyone building a passive income portfolio, this monthly cash flow can perfectly match living expenses or accelerate compounding when reinvested.</p>

        <h3>Risks of Monthly Dividend Stocks</h3>
        <p>Don't just chase the yield. Monthly payers come with unique risks you must understand:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Yield Traps:</strong> A very high yield (e.g., 10%+) is often a warning sign that the stock price has collapsed and the dividend is about to be cut.</li>
          <li><strong>Interest Rate Sensitivity:</strong> REITs and BDCs rely heavily on borrowing. When interest rates rise, their borrowing costs go up, which can squeeze their profit margins and threaten the dividend.</li>
          <li><strong>Tax Implications:</strong> Because REITs and BDCs avoid corporate taxes by passing income to shareholders, those dividends are generally taxed as ordinary income, not at the lower "qualified dividend" rates.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Building a Monthly Income Portfolio</h3>
        <p>If you want monthly income, you don't necessarily have to restrict yourself to monthly payers. You can build a portfolio of high-quality quarterly payers whose payment schedules stagger across the year (e.g., one pays Jan/Apr/Jul/Oct, another Feb/May/Aug/Nov, etc.). However, true monthly payers offer simplicity and immediate gratification.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="picks-section">
      <h2>Top Monthly Dividend Stocks to Consider</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">We've highlighted some of the most prominent monthly payers across key sectors like Real Estate (REITs) and Business Development Companies (BDCs).</p>

      <div class="picks-grid">
        <div class="pick-group">
          <h3>Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs)</h3>
          <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-bottom:16px;">Companies that own and operate income-producing real estate like retail stores, warehouses, or apartments.</p>

          <div class="stock-item">
            <div class="stock-header">
              <div><span class="stock-ticker">O</span> <span class="stock-name">Realty Income</span></div>
              <div class="stock-yield">~5.6%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stock-stats"><span>Sector: Real Estate</span><span>Market Cap: $50B+</span><span>Streak: 30+ yrs</span></div>
            <div class="stock-desc">Known as "The Monthly Dividend Company," Realty Income owns over 13,000 freestanding commercial properties. It's a Dividend Aristocrat and the gold standard for monthly income.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="stock-item">
            <div class="stock-header">
              <div><span class="stock-ticker">STAG</span> <span class="stock-name">STAG Industrial</span></div>
              <div class="stock-yield">~3.9%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stock-stats"><span>Sector: Real Estate</span><span>Market Cap: $7B+</span><span>Streak: 12 yrs</span></div>
            <div class="stock-desc">A pure-play industrial REIT focused on single-tenant industrial properties across the US, benefiting massively from the long-term growth of e-commerce and domestic logistics.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="stock-item">
            <div class="stock-header">
              <div><span class="stock-ticker">ADC</span> <span class="stock-name">Agree Realty</span></div>
              <div class="stock-yield">~4.8%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stock-stats"><span>Sector: Real Estate</span><span>Market Cap: $6B+</span><span>Streak: 10 yrs</span></div>
            <div class="stock-desc">A retail REIT that focuses almost exclusively on industry-leading, omni-channel retail tenants (like Walmart, Tractor Supply, and Home Depot) with strong balance sheets.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pick-group">
          <h3>Business Development Companies (BDCs)</h3>
          <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-bottom:16px;">Firms that provide financing to small and mid-sized private companies.</p>

          <div class="stock-item">
            <div class="stock-header">
              <div><span class="stock-ticker">MAIN</span> <span class="stock-name">Main Street Capital</span></div>
              <div class="stock-yield">~6.0%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stock-stats"><span>Sector: Financials</span><span>Market Cap: $4B+</span><span>Streak: 10+ yrs</span></div>
            <div class="stock-desc">One of the most respected BDCs in the market, providing debt and equity capital to lower-middle market companies. Often pays special dividends on top of its regular monthly payout.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="stock-item">
            <div class="stock-header">
              <div><span class="stock-ticker">GLAD</span> <span class="stock-name">Gladstone Capital</span></div>
              <div class="stock-yield">~9.5%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stock-stats"><span>Sector: Financials</span><span>Market Cap: $800M+</span><span>Streak: Var yrs</span></div>
            <div class="stock-desc">A higher-yielding BDC that focuses on senior debt securities of lower middle market companies. Carries more risk than MAIN but offers a significantly higher current yield.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="table-section">
      <h2>Compare Monthly Dividend Stocks</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Use the interactive table below to sort and filter through a curated list of reliable monthly dividend payers.</p>

      <div class="controls">
        <input type="text" id="stock-search" placeholder="Search by ticker or name…">
        <select id="categoryFilter">
          <option value="">All Categories</option>
          <option value="REIT">REIT</option>
          <option value="BDC">BDC</option>
          <option value="CEF">CEF / Fund</option>
          <option value="Other">Other</option>
        </select>
      </div>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table id="stock-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th data-key="ticker">Ticker</th>
              <th data-key="name">Company Name</th>
              <th data-key="category">Category</th>
              <th data-key="yield" data-type="num">Yield</th>
              <th data-key="growth" data-type="num">5Y Div Growth</th>
              <th data-key="years" data-type="num">Growth Streak</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody id="stock-tbody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div id="faq"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="related-section">
      <h2>Related Research</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/best-dividend-stocks-for-beginners" class="related-card">
          <h3>Best Dividend Stocks for Beginners</h3>
          <p>Explore 15 solid starter picks including Dividend Kings and reliable growth stocks.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/best-monthly-dividend-etfs" class="related-card">
          <h3>Best Monthly Dividend ETFs</h3>
          <p>Prefer ETFs? Compare JEPI, JEPQ, and other top funds that pay monthly.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/dividend-aristocrats" class="related-card">
          <h3>Dividend Aristocrats Complete List</h3>
          <p>Discover the S&P 500 companies with 25+ consecutive years of dividend growth.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    const STOCK_DATA = [
      { ticker: "O", name: "Realty Income", category: "REIT", yield: 5.6, growth: 3.2, years: 30 },
      { ticker: "STAG", name: "STAG Industrial", category: "REIT", yield: 3.9, growth: 0.8, years: 12 },
      { ticker: "ADC", name: "Agree Realty", category: "REIT", yield: 4.8, growth: 5.9, years: 10 },
      { ticker: "EPR", name: "EPR Properties", category: "REIT", yield: 7.2, growth: -5.0, years: 2 },
      { ticker: "MAIN", name: "Main Street Capital", category: "BDC", yield: 6.0, growth: 4.1, years: 10 },
      { ticker: "GLAD", name: "Gladstone Capital", category: "BDC", yield: 9.5, growth: 2.0, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "PSEC", name: "Prospect Capital", category: "BDC", yield: 12.1, growth: -1.0, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "UTG", name: "Reaves Utility Income", category: "CEF", yield: 7.8, growth: 1.5, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "DNP", name: "DNP Select Income", category: "CEF", yield: 8.1, growth: 0.0, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "LTC", name: "LTC Properties", category: "REIT", yield: 6.8, growth: 0.0, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "SLG", name: "SL Green Realty", category: "REIT", yield: 6.1, growth: -3.5, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "PBA", name: "Pembina Pipeline", category: "Other", yield: 5.5, growth: 2.2, years: 0 },
      { ticker: "HRZN", name: "Horizon Technology", category: "BDC", yield: 10.5, growth: 1.1, years: 0 }
    ];

    const FAQ = [
      { q: "Why do some companies pay dividends monthly instead of quarterly?", a: "Most companies pay quarterly because it aligns with their financial reporting cycle. However, some companies—especially Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs) and Business Development Companies (BDCs)—choose to pay monthly to attract income investors who rely on a steady cash flow to pay living expenses." },
      { q: "Are monthly dividend stocks safe?", a: "The frequency of the payout doesn't determine a stock's safety; the underlying business does. While companies like Realty Income (O) are considered very stable, some monthly payers (like certain Closed-End Funds or high-yield mortgage REITs) can be highly volatile and carry significant risk of dividend cuts." },
      { q: "What is a REIT?", a: "A Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) is a company that owns, operates, or finances income-generating real estate. By law, REITs must pay out at least 90% of their taxable income to shareholders as dividends, which is why they often have higher yields and sometimes pay monthly." },
      { q: "What is a BDC?", a: "A Business Development Company (BDC) is an organization that invests in small- and medium-sized businesses, often providing them with debt or equity financing. Like REITs, BDCs are required to distribute over 90% of their profits to shareholders, leading to high dividend yields." },
      { q: "How are monthly dividends from REITs and BDCs taxed?", a: "Unlike \"qualified dividends\" from regular corporations (which get favorable tax rates), dividends from REITs and BDCs are usually considered ordinary income and are taxed at your regular income tax bracket. For this reason, many investors prefer to hold them in tax-advantaged accounts like an IRA or TFSA." }
    ];

    function renderStocks(data) {
      const tbody = document.getElementById('stock-tbody');
      tbody.innerHTML = data.map(s => {
        const yc = s.yield >= 8 ? 'yield-high' : s.yield >= 5 ? 'yield-mid' : 'yield-low';
        return `<tr>
          <td class="ticker">${s.ticker}</td>
          <td>${s.name}</td>
          <td>${s.category}</td>
          <td class="num ${yc}">${s.yield.toFixed(1)}%</td>
          <td class="num">${s.growth > 0 ? '+' : ''}${s.growth.toFixed(1)}%</td>
          <td class="num">${s.years}</td>
        </tr>`;
      }).join('');
    }

    function renderFAQ() {
      const container = document.getElementById('faq');
      container.innerHTML = FAQ.map(f => `
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">${f.q}</div>
          <div class="faq-a">${f.a}</div>
        </div>
      `).join('');

      container.querySelectorAll('.faq-q').forEach(q => {
        q.addEventListener('click', () => q.parentElement.classList.toggle('open'));
      });
    }

    let stockSortKey = 'yield';
    let stockSortDir = 'desc';
    let stockData = [...STOCK_DATA];

    function applySort() {
      stockData.sort((a, b) => {
        let av = a[stockSortKey];
        let bv = b[stockSortKey];
        if (typeof av === 'string') av = av.toLowerCase();
        if (typeof bv === 'string') bv = bv.toLowerCase();

        if (av < bv) return stockSortDir === 'asc' ? -1 : 1;
        if (av > bv) return stockSortDir === 'asc' ? 1 : -1;
        return 0;
      });

      document.querySelectorAll('#stock-table th').forEach(th => {
        th.classList.remove('sorted-asc', 'sorted-desc');
        if (th.dataset.key === stockSortKey) {
          th.classList.add('sorted-' + stockSortDir);
        }
      });

      renderStocks(stockData);
    }

    function handleSortClick(key, type) {
      if (stockSortKey === key) {
        stockSortDir = stockSortDir === 'asc' ? 'desc' : 'asc';
      } else {
        stockSortKey = key;
        stockSortDir = type === 'num' ? 'desc' : 'asc';
      }
      applySort();
    }

    document.querySelectorAll('#stock-table th[data-key]').forEach(th => {
      th.addEventListener('click', () => handleSortClick(th.dataset.key, th.dataset.type));
    });

    function filterData() {
      const q = document.getElementById('stock-search').value.toLowerCase();
      const catVal = document.getElementById('categoryFilter').value;

      stockData = STOCK_DATA.filter(s => {
        const matchSearch = !q || s.ticker.toLowerCase().includes(q) || s.name.toLowerCase().includes(q);
        const matchCat = !catVal || s.category === catVal;
        return matchSearch && matchCat;
      });

      applySort();
    }

    document.getElementById('stock-search').addEventListener('input', filterData);
    document.getElementById('categoryFilter').addEventListener('change', filterData);

    // Initialize
    renderFAQ();
    applySort(); // Uses default sort key 'yield' and dir 'desc'
  </script>
</SiteLayout>